Lab One Visualization and Data Preprocessing
¶

2017-2018 California Department of Education Mathmematics Achievement
Create by An Nguyen, Andy Ho, Jodi Pafford, Tori Wheelis
¶
January 25, 2019

Business Understanding¶

    This dataset contains information from schools within the California Department of Education. It specifically addresses school progress on standardized tests in Mathematics during the 2017-2018 school year. In part, the data will be used to support Local Education Agencies (LEA) in identifying strengths, weaknesses, and areas for improvement; assist in determining whether LEAs are eligible for assistance; and assist the SSPI in determining whether LEAs are eligible for more intensive state support/intervention. The school accountability system in California has 10 priorities. This dataset looks at one part of the 4th priority: Student Achievement. The dataset used in this analysis pertains specifically to its Mathematics curriculum and the progress made from 2017 school year and the 2018 school year.

    From this dataset, we will look at how the state, each county, LEA, and campus increased or decreased their average distance above or below the passing standard score. This dataset also allows us to look at different programs (English Learner, Socioeconomic Disadvantaged, Students with Disabilities, Foster Youth, Homeless Youth) and race/ethnicities (Black/African American, American Indian or Alaska Native, Asian, Filipino, Hispanic, Pacific Islander, White, Multiples Races/Two or More). This project will address what difference in performance progress were seen between public and charter schools and its respective population subgroups, as described above. The outcome from this will provide further insights to California on the following:

  • Is one subgroup out/underperforming another?
  • How do districts compare performance wise? County Offices of Education? What about with subgroups?
  • Charter v. Traditional schools? What about with subgroups?
  • Any impacts/trends by # of kids tested?

Data is important because:

  • It tells you how students performed on the California Assessment of Student Performance and Progress (CAASPP), california's state wide test.
  • It tells you what achievement/performance gaps exist - so policy can be made to address these issues.

Data Quality¶

    At first glance, you will notice that the All category total in any line is less adding up all the lines for similar campuses. This is happening because a student may be in several different categories (i.e., a student may be White (WH), in foster care (FOS), be living in a low socio-economic status (SED) and be served by special education (SWD) student will count in 4 of the 16 categories listed). No edits were needed for this phenomenon, we need to be aware of this as we move forward.

    Additionally, there were columns of data that we choose to eliminate from the data altogether. There were 7 columns at the end of the dataset that give the data for the California Alternate Assessment. This test is usually given to students served by special education who have profound disabilities and are unable to complete the same test as others. There are approximately 1% of the total population who are included, and the data does not support our current research, therefore, these columns are also deleted.

In [74]:
#Delete most of the ending columns that are all about alternate testing: profound disabilities (all the 'caa_...' columns)
#Delete reporting year (not needed since all data is 2018)

math2018.drop(['caa_denom', 'caa_level1_num', 'caa_level1_pct', 'caa_level2_num', 'caa_level2_pct', 'caa_level3_num', 'caa_level3_pct', 'ReportingYear'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    Next, we found a column of data called pairshare_method. If a campus does not include students of a testing grade level (i.e. PK campuses) or the campus only serves special populations (i.e., mental health hospital), the data is often paired with another campus in the district or charter. If we kept this data in our dataset, these would be duplicates. Therefore, the lines of data were deleted and then the column was deleted.

In [75]:
#We can also delete rows of data for campuses that are pairshare_method ('CA', 'DA', 'WA')
#there are 91 rows of data we can remove this way.
#Pairshare means that their scores were shared with another campus

math2018.drop(math2018[(math2018.pairshare_method == 'CA') | (math2018.pairshare_method == 'DA') | (math2018.pairshare_method == 'WA')].index, inplace=True)

#Now that those lines have been deleted, we can eliminate the pairshare_method 

math2018.drop(['pairshare_method'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    There are many missing values, however, they are not mistakes. The values that are missing appear when a population has 10 or fewer students represented. When this occurs, the data is not calculated for the purpose of this data file and state accountability ratings. As we look at the data, you will notice some of the larger category averages come out to NaN (Not a Number) because each individual total is 10 or fewer. We chose to delete these lines from our dataset because the data we need to calculate is not included for these lines.

In [76]:
#Delete any row of data where there is no Currstatus data - meaning that there were less than 10 students that make up that group

math2018.dropna(subset=["currstatus"], inplace=True)

Explore Joint Attributes¶

    In order to get a better look at the SchoolType and the studentgroup, we created a new attribute, School Type. After doing so, we used groupby to create a group-wise average. Once the new column, called "SchoolType" was created, the former columns were deleted.

In [80]:
#Create a new column, SchoolType; label each row with an appropriate label: state, county, district, public, charter, alternative public, and alternative charter

math2018.loc[(math2018.charter_flag == 'Y') & (math2018.dass_flag != 'Y'), 'SchoolType'] = 'Charter'
math2018.loc[(math2018.charter_flag == 'Y') & (math2018.dass_flag == 'Y'), 'SchoolType'] = 'AltCharter'
math2018.loc[math2018.coe_flag == 'Y', 'SchoolType'] = 'County'
math2018.loc[(math2018.dass_flag == 'Y') & (math2018.charter_flag != 'Y'), 'SchoolType'] = 'AltPublic'
math2018.loc[(math2018.rtype == 'S') & (math2018.charter_flag != 'Y') & (math2018.dass_flag != 'Y'), 'SchoolType'] = 'Public'
math2018.loc[(math2018.rtype == 'X'), 'SchoolType'] = 'State'
math2018.loc[(math2018.rtype == 'D') & (math2018.coe_flag != 'Y'), 'SchoolType'] = 'District'

#Delete columns that are no longer necessary now that the school type is combined (rtype, charter_flag, coe_flag, dass_flag)

math2018.drop(['rtype', 'charter_flag', 'coe_flag', 'dass_flag'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    As we explored the data further, we found the need to drop a few more aspects of our data set. One final step in the initial cleaning process was to remove the State, County and District lines of data. Leaving these lines of data in the file, leads to duplicates. Every school belongs to 3 larger organizations - it's respective district, county, and state.

In [81]:
math2018.drop(math2018[(math2018.SchoolType=='State') | (math2018.SchoolType=='County') | (math2018.SchoolType=='District')].index, inplace=True)
In [82]:
#Group School Type and Student Group and report average distance from 'passing' for 2018

math2018_grouped= math2018.groupby(by=['SchoolType', 'studentgroup'])
math2018_AvgDistance = math2018_grouped.currstatus.sum() / math2018_grouped.currstatus.count()

Explore Attributes and Class¶

    From the above twon tables it is clear that Alternative schools, whether in the public or charter settings perform worse than their "regular" counterpart. With the exception of the Filipino student group that seems to excel in the public alternative school setting, performing bettern then their counterparts in charter and public schools. Alternatively, the foster children in the school systems requires attention. They are the worse performing group within the public shool system. Although we do not have enough data on foster children within the alternative school systems to compare it is still worth noting that the foster children within the charter school system performs comparably with the general populations of the alternative school systems surpassing their peers.

New Features¶

    As mentioned above, the data is presented in such a way that made comparing different school types difficult. There are various columns with a 'Y' or blank entry, each based on the data being from either a Charter School, County Entity, or an Alternative School (3 separate columns). Additionally, there is another column that tells us if the data is from either state, district/LEA, or school (1 column). In order to get one label for each line of data based on this data, a new feature was created called SchoolType. The New feature created was, "SchoolType". Based on the 4 columns mentioned above, SchoolType attributes are Public, Charter, AltPublic, AltCharter, District, County, and State. (see code from Explore Attributes)

Exceptional Work¶

<p align = "justify">    Using the number of students that sat the math exam, currdenom, from all the school as the input variable and the distance from passing for each school, currstatus of the 'ALL' group. We attempt to ascertain the 5 most important student groups responsible for the status of the school. Since there is only one response variable a univariate approach to feature selection. The continous nature of the response variable lend itself for us to use the f_regression scoring function.</p>

<p align = "justify">    According to the model the top five student groups that has the greatest effect on a school's statust is Asian, Multiple Races, White, English Only and Socioeconomically Disadvantaged students. The distribution of the number of students within each student group did not have a normal distribution. We log transformed all the variable except for the response variable and reran the feature selection. The same five student group appeared but in different order; English Only, White, Asian, Multiple Races, Socioeconomically Disadvantaged students.</p>

#perform univariate feature selection
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest
from sklearn.feature_selection import f_regression

def featureselection(table):
    array = table.values #change pandas dataframe to numpy array
    array[np.isnan(array)] = 0 #impute all NaN to 0
    _input = array[:,0:16] #parse out features to be filtered
    _target = array[:,16] #parse out response variable

    #feature selecton using SelectKBest with f_regression as scoring function
    test = SelectKBest(score_func=f_regression, k=4)
    fit = test.fit(_input, _target)
    features = fit.transform(_input)

    #match scores to feature names and display
    index=list(table)[:-1]
    np.set_printoptions(precision=3) 
    values=fit.scores_
    featurescores = pd.DataFrame(values, index=index, columns=["scores"])
    featurescores.sort_values(by=['scores'], inplace=True, ascending=False)
    print(featurescores[:5])
    
featureselection(newtable)
